@Barry Ancona - I myself bristled when I read an article (I believe in Natural History) written by a botanist who just matter-of-factly mentioned that green algae were plants. So I went on a little investigation and found out about the newer classification schemes. The protista are such a problematic group, and trying to classify organisms  in a way that makes evolutionary sense, almost demands that some of the algae be lumped in with the land plants. 

I would imagine some people also gnashed their teeth at the idea that birds are reptiles, but I wasn't one of them when that came around many years ago. It was obvious that this was the case to anyone familiar with vertebrate evolution. The plant/alga situation is not exactly parallel to the bird/dinosaur/reptile situation, but they are somewhat comparable. 

FYI, a case could be made that mammals are also reptiles, but modern re-definitions of reptiles exclude that possibility -- I do wonder if reptiles were redefined merely to exclude the mammals!

